Today was our baby girl’s due date 🙏🏻 | Hoy era mi fecha prevista de parto 👀

✄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄ 

But… she decided to show up 3 weeks earlier 😅
As someone that LOVES to plan everything this certainly stressed me out and took me (us!) by surprise.

But I remember walking to the hospital and there were two men talking on the sidewalk and as we walked past them, one said: “You know what they say… everything happens for a reason” ✨

And maybe this was silly, but I decided to take that as a *sign from the universe*: everything would be alright, even if it was earlier than anticipated.

Ps: this was the view from our room at hospital, with views of the Summit, the Chrysler building and more… our lucky gal born in Manhattan 😅🤭💖

✄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄ 

Pero... ella decidió llegar 3 semanas antes 😅
Y se imaginarán que siendo yo una persona a quien le ENCANTA planificar todo, esto ciertamente me estresó y me tomó (¡nos tomó!) por sorpresa.

Pero me acuerdo estar caminando hacia el hospital y había dos hombres hablando en la vereda y cuando pasamos junto a ellos, uno dijo: “Ya sabes lo que dicen… todo pasa por algo” (“You know what they say… everything happens for a reason”) ✨

Y tal vez esto fue una tontería, pero decidí tomar eso como una *señal del universo*: todo iba a estar bien, incluso siendo antes de lo previsto.

PD: esta fue la vista desde nuestra habitación en el hospital, con vistas al Summit, al edificio Chrysler y más... nuestra chica afortunada nacida en Manhattan 😅🤭💖 jajaja

“I'm not like a regular mom. I'm a cool mom.” 💁🏻‍♀️

✄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄ 

Thought these photos and videos deserved a spot on the feed!
Plus it’s my first look of the day with a STROLLER! That’s a first 😅😅

In all seriousness, when I was pregnant one of the things that I would think often was about this whole “cool mom” idea. I know the quote is intended to be a joke but I was/am afraid of is this idea that when you become a mom that’s all you are, a mom.

And while I understand this might be true for some people (and exactly what they want!) I was/am scared of losing my personal style (truth be told I am scared of A WHOLE LOT more serious things but we’ll only talk about this for now haha).
Getting dressed is something I enjoy and that has in a way defined who I am for many, many years now.

Happy to report that being pregnant and now being a mom, I was/am able to still dress how I like, how I feel comfortable, how I feel beautiful. I am/was able to still have a personal style and sense of self, and to still be many things in life, and also be a mom 🥹🫶🏻

✄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄ 

¡Pensé que estas fotos y videos merecían un lugar en el feed!
¡Además, es mi primer look del día con un COCHECITO! 😅😅

Hablando en serio, cuando estaba embarazada, una de las cosas que pensaba seguido era en todo este asunto de la "mamá cool". Sé que la frase pretende ser un chiste, pero tenía/tengo miedo de esta idea de que cuando te convertis en mamá, eso es todo lo que sos, una mamá.
Y aunque entiendo que esto puede ser cierto para algunas personas (¡y exactamente lo que quieren!), tenía/tengo miedo de perder mi estilo personal (a decir verdad, tengo miedo de MUCHAS cosas más serias, pero solo vamos a hablar de esto por ahora jaja).
Vestirme es algo que disfruto y que de alguna manera ha definido quién soy durante muchos, muchos años.

Pero… me pone contenta contarles que estando embarazada y ahora siendo mamá, todavía puedo vestirme como me gusta, cómo me siento cómoda, cómo me siento linda. Puedo/pude tener todavía un estilo personal y un sentido de mí misma, y ​​seguir siendo muchas cosas en la vida, y también ser mamá 🥹🫶🏻

One of the perks of having a newborn? That they wake you up very early in the am for you to see the beautiful sunrises 😍🤣😝

5 years ago, making memories in Park City ❄️ | Hace cinco años, conociendo la mágica ciudad de Park City, uno de los mejores centros de ski 🎿 

✄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄ 

Amazing trip with #teampixel and @googlepixel, when are we going back? 👀👀

While we are still waiting for the ❄️ first snow day ❄️ of the season in NYC, here’s what Central Park looked liked on January of last year…

In fact, do you that we’re currently in the middle of the second-longest snow-free streak? 😰😰 Today marks the 320th consecutive day without “measurable snowfall” (0.1 inches or more) and there is not much in the forecast either 🥺🥺🥺

We have seen some flakes but it’s only fallen in small amounts, and often been mixed with rain (like today!) 

The last time NYC saw snow for the first time this late in the winter was back in 1973 (!!!) when the city didn’t receive any significant snowfall until January 29, and there’s a chance we may beat this record this year 😳😳😳

✄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄ 

Mientras todavía esperamos el ❄️ primer día de nieve ❄️ de la temporada en Nueva York, así es como se veía Central Park en enero del año pasado...

De hecho, ¿sabes que actualmente estamos en medio de la segunda racha más larga sin nieve? 😰😰 Hoy se cumplen 320 días consecutivos sin “nevadas medibles” (2.5 milímetros o más) y tampoco hay mucho en el pronóstico 🥺🥺🥺

Hemos visto algunos copos, pero solo han caído en pequeñas cantidades y, a menudo, se han mezclado con lluvia (¡como hoy!)

La última vez que NYC vio nieve por primera vez tan tarde en el invierno fue en 1973 (!!!) cuando la ciudad no recibió ninguna nevada significativa hasta el 29 de enero, y existe la posibilidad de que superemos este récord este año 😳 😳😳

✄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄

“The days are long but the years are short” goes the saying and it I SO true.
January went by in the blink of an eye, and just like that 1/12 of 2023 is gone…
So this year, I am trying to not only make more memories, but to remember more of what happened:

- Our first time going to Central Park as a family of 4 on my birthday weekend (my birthday itself was not the best day… but we went again the next day and had the best time… so if you can, take that second chance 🥹)
- Adjusting to our day-to-day life as working parents… and the three of us having a nasty cold for about a week 🫠
- Finally got my driver license 🪪  and Julia’s US passport!
- One of our best friends here in NYC met our baby for the first time 🫶🏻
- Oreo 🤍
- Going for walks with the stroller ✨
- Weekly video calls with my mom and sister 📞
- Worked out 21 days of the month 💪🏻
- Julia started to smile and see and understand more of the world 😭
- Breakfasts in bed while nursing ☕️ 
- Finished 3 books 📚

February here we come!

✄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄ 

“Los días son largos pero los años son cortos” dice el dicho y es MUY cierto.
Enero pasó en un abrir y cerrar de ojos, y así se fue el 1/12 de 2023…
Entonces, este año, estoy tratando no solo de crear más recuerdos, sino de recordar más de lo que sucedió:

- Fuimos por primera vez a Central Park como una familia de 4 en el fin de semana de mi cumpleaños (mi cumpleaños en sí no fue el mejor día... pero fuimos de nuevo al día siguiente y lo pasamos genial... así que si podes, aprovecha esa segunda oportunidad 🥹)
- Adaptándonos a nuestra vida como mapadres que trabajan... y los tres con un tremendo resfrío durante aproximadamente una semana 🫠
- ¡Finalmente obtuve mi registro de conducir 🪪 y el pasaporte estadounidense de Juli!
- Uno de nuestros mejores amigos acá en NY conoció a nuestra bebé por primera vez 🫶🏻
- Oreo 🤍
- Caminatas con el cochecito ✨
- Videollamadas semanales con mi mamá y mi hermana 📞
- Hice ejercicio 21 días del mes 💪🏻
- Julia empezando a sonreír y a ver y entender más del mundo 😭
- Desayunos en la cama mientras amamanto ☕️

As you know if you watched my stories, this edition of NYFW was a bit different. As a new mom and nursing, it was not that easy to be running around town (and tbh I was really tired to even try to do that haha)
But I did go to some shows and had a wonderful time!

This is what I wore on my first day of events and I wanted to share a bit of the thought process behind it.
With every new edition of NYFW I’m really eager to style new clothes and wear crazy outfits but at the same time I want to be… me. And being me means wearing clothes I already own and styling them in a different way, it means wearing outfits I’d wear on any other day as well, and it means staying true to my personal style ✨

✄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄

The shortest month of the year went by in the blink of an eye, as you might expect.

- Giving other people the chance to attend events on my behalf 
- Tiny lovely everyday moments with Tom and Julia
- Filming again for YouTube (season 2023 of the channel is here!)
- Oreo 🤍
- Making the time to see friends at events, for lunch, for dinner (something I am really working towards… having people I can trust and rely on here in the city)
- Working out 8 days of the month… could have been better, but I also hurt my right ankle and hip so…

This was New York in October of 2014, the month Taylor Swift’s album 1989 first came out.
I had met a boy just 6 months prior and we fell for one another, even though we both knew he was about to move abroad.
He lived in Portland, Oregon and I lived in Buenos Aires, Argentina, and New York was OUR place. The city where we would meet and dream about what our future could one day be.
“Everybody here wanted somethin' more” and we certainly did, but we just didn’t know how to make those dreams our reality… at least not yet.
New York was our escape, the city where we would meet again and again, month after month, plotting, daydreaming, imagining what if…
1989 was an album we listened to, together, and also 6,830 miles apart. It was an album that in a way I felt described myself, this version of me of 2014, the one that was struggling, the one that wanted to find love, the one that wanted to one day move to New York.
Almost 9 years later a lot has changed. That boy is now my husband, we have two daughters (one dog and one human), and New York is our home. We had our ups and downs, we moved away, we came back, we sometimes think of leaving the city, we sometimes feel like we could never do that. Some of our dreams became realities, some others we are still working on.
But you know what? I wouldn't change anything, anything, anything.

I’ve been living in NYC for 5 years.
I first moved here from Argentina in July of 2016 and relocated to Germany in September of 2019. We then came back in October of 2021 and have been here ever since.
So the math is not exactly precise, but I’d say July is still in a way this “anniversary month” for me.

5 years here means I no longer feel the city as a strange place. I’ve been to the each of the 5 boroughs many times, and sometimes when walking around certain neighborhoods I feel as if I have memories in every corner, from many seasons.

5 years here means I am halfway of what most people consider a real New Yorker. Personally, some days I feel like one, and some others I’m still trying to find who I really am in between this mix of countries, cities and languages spoken.

We sometimes dream of getting a big house with a backyard somewhere else (cause the prices in the city are always insane). And then I think about being away of this crazy beautiful city and it breaks my heart. 

So… I truly don’t know what the future has in store for us. But hey, one way or the other, cheers to 5 years! 5 years of living and loving NYC.

As I write this I am heading off to my first event for this new edition of NYFW.
This will be the 12th edition I’ll be attending and at times I seriously can’t believe it.

I was not always interested in fashion (or at least not that I can recall) but when I turned 18 and got my first job, one of the things I would buy with *my own money* were fashion magazines. 
The shows I saw in photos, happening in NYC and in Europe looked surreal and also unattainable.
But still I thought: imagine if one day I could attend a show, just ONE show… that would be… amazing.
And… here we are so many years later. I have attended so many shows that I have honestly lost count, but i think they are almost 100? (like what?!)

Every February and every September I plan out my weeks, my outfits, I get stressed and nervous but also filled with joy every time a new invite lands on my inbox or a brand finally says yes to my request after so many rejections.

I’m not going to say “believe in your dreams, they come true!” But instead: work for your dreams. Send those emails. Get rejected. Reach out again and again. Show up. Show your work. Build connections. Build confidence. Deliver. And then do it all over again.

Cheers to a new edition! And thank you for being there along this long road 🫶🏻

First CHRISTMAS TREE lighting ceremony 🎄 | Primera ceremonia de encendido del ARBOL de NAVIDAD

✄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄ 

In December of 1912, Madison Square Park was the site of the country’s first public Christmas tree lighting ceremony.

The idea of a public Christmas tree was first proposed by Emilie D. Lee Herreshoff (the socialite wife of a prominent chemical scientist) as a way to allow all New Yorkers, rich and poor, to enjoy the home holiday tradition.

That year, the Park attracted 25,000 visitors and became the country’s first public Christmas tree lighting, featuring electric twinkling lights at a time when electric lighting was not yet common throughout the US.

All this to say that I personally didn’t know that Madison Square Park had a Christmas Tree until this year and I HAD to visit! 
In the video on the second slide you can see the “Star of Hope” monument, which marks the approximate location of the first tree lighting in Madison Square Park.

En diciembre de 1912, Madison Square Park fue el sitio de la primera ceremonia pública de iluminación de un árbol de Navidad del país.

La idea de un árbol de Navidad público fue propuesta por primera vez por Emilie D. Lee Herreshoff (la esposa socialité de un destacado científico químico) como una forma de permitir que todos los neoyorquinos, ricos y pobres, disfruten de la tradición de las fiestas.

Ese año, el parque atrajo a 25,000 visitantes y se convirtió en la primera iluminación pública del árbol de Navidad del país, con luces eléctricas centelleantes en un momento en que la iluminación eléctrica aún no era común en todo Estados Unidos.

Toda esta intro para contarles que yo no sabía que Madison Square Park tenía un árbol de Navidad hasta este año, pero apenas me enteré tuve que visitarlo.
En el video que pueden ver deslizando hacia la izquierda, se ve el Monumento “Star of Hope”, que marca la ubicación aproximada de la primera iluminación del árbol en el Madison Square Park.

I have been holding on to these photos for a year… | Estoy guardando estas fotos hace un año…

✄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄┄ 

These were taken by stranger in January of 2023, who later approached us and airdropped them. (For the record I didn’t think this was creepy but rather cute and kind, she thought we might want them as a nice memory)

I have looked at them and thought about sharing them on Instagram for months, but always decided against it. 

We were here on one of our walks around the neighborhood. One of the -I think- hundred of walks we’ve probably taken together around NYC as a new family of 4 during 2023.

But this walk and the many we took in the winter months were different. I called them our “mental health walks”. I was not going through the best time -mentally- after Julia was born. Postpartum depression is not only real, but hard to work on, because duh, you have a newborn, and they need you for everything, so there’s -literally- no time to focus on you and your wellbeing. And being a new parent also puts the relationship with your partner to the test every single day.

So those winter months were… tough. And every time I saw these photos I had this lump form in my throat cause I remembered how we sometimes took these walks just to… survive.

But seeing as this transformative year is coming to an end, I thought I’d set these photos free. Posting them and sharing the story behind them feels liberating. We made it to the other side of the tunnel. We survived.

Because this year was full of struggles, full of changes, full of tears, full of challenges, but also so full of joy, of laughter, of love, of growth. And that is… life.

So my wish to you reading this message is that you will be kind enough to yourself to appreciate what you did this year, even if 2023 is not a reel of beautiful highlights. If you survived this year, with everything that was thrown at you, you did enough, and you should be proud of that. 

So here’s to 2024! We are ready, cheers 🥂
